description.text:
This is a customizable clamp for mounting a laser diode (or other cylindrical objects) on an optics mounting post. The default STLs are for a 12mm diode on an 8mm post with M3 bolts and nuts.

This component was inspired by the Open-source optics project, whose goal is to radically reduce the cost of scientific optical hardware, by the Michigan Tech's Open Sustainability Technology Research Group.

UPDATE: now slightly smaller, using measured sizes (and some leeway) for the nut to reduce slot size. And tighter on the post/rod.

This prints well at 0.2mm layers or finer, and I didn't need supports on my printers.

PLA works, but is fragile (don't over tighten!). ABS works better, but may not be compatible with some plastic diode housings. My Acrylate test broke pretty quickly, but could vary depending on the material flexibility. Sintered nylon is almost too soft, but still works. Of course, if the material is too flexible then the clamp won't hold the diode in place.

description.text:
This is a 1/24 scale model of a Zimmer Quicksilver. You may know that the Pontiac Fiero, with its mid-engine layout, plastic body panels, and dirt-cheap used price, is a great starting point for a kit car playing dress-up as something more expensive. What you may not know is people started taking advantage of this while the car was still new, first with some not-quite-legal dealer-built Ferrari replicas, and then with this.
Zimmer is a company that builds "neo-classical" cars, which usually involves adding 1930s-style front and rear bodywork to a modern car, while retaining the shape of the passenger compartment. The Quicksilver is a more cohesive design than any other Zimmer, because it was styled by Don Johnson, who was working for GM at the time. They stretched the Fiero chassis by 16 inches, which is still 2/3 of an inch at 1/24 scale, so this is kind of a big print.

You can print the car body as one big piece, or the Xtra Detail version, which splits the bumpers and sills into separate parts. You can flip those parts to print in different orientations if you want, but I'm not sure if they'll look much better and the pins that attach them to the body already aren't oriented in the strongest position.
You can also choose to print the wheels as one piece or separated into "tires" and "hubcaps" (not exactly the right terms for the parts as represented, but it does give all the files different names). You may want to print the hubcaps at .1 resolution. The tire sizes are staggered, so you need to print 2 prints and 2 rears either way.
Print 4 pins to attach the wheels.
I printed everything but the wheels/tires and hubcaps with support, and used helper discs on the ends of the sills and bumpers.
Everything is snap-fit. The hubcaps are a tight fit, you will probably have to sand around the edge.

print_settings.Notes:: I wouldn't print this in PLA. Getting the card in requires quite a bit of flexing of the retaining tab, so more flexible plastic like ABS or PETG would be better. I use ABS and it's worked perfectly. Further, an ID badge is the sort of thing you might leave in your car by accident or design, and PLA deforms very quickly in summer car temperatures. It is entirely possible that the PLA will flex enough, as the back/tab is very thin and that makes it more flexible - I just wouldn't bother due to the many shortcomings of PLA for this purpose. Similarly I wouldn't do this in a truly flexible plastic like TPU or Ninjaflex or what have you. It's not needed, and could work against the purpose of the thing.

description.text:
A friend at work asked for "something LA Dodgers" but I thought just printing the logo would be boring. Then he broke his card holder.

I'd printed the badge holder previously and it was a little flimsy because the back is so thin. It's not really possible to thicken just the back, because then the clip is either too thick or off the build plate, and I'm allergic to supports.

Adding the LA logo to the back makes it much less fiddly, and also kills two birds with one stone.

Printer:

Folger Tech Kossel Rev B

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

100%

Notes:

Unless you need to use a raft due to perforated plate or shockingly un-level build plate, I would avoid it like the plague. The back of the holder is so thin that it will be hard to recover from the air gap and not be terrible. If you don't need the air gap because you are using soluble supports, you can clearly do anything you want because you have cheater plastic to magic all of the flaws away.

Actual infill doesn't matter, just do 3 or 4 perimeters and it's solid. It's not that thick a piece.

Original version of the badge required some scaling down, but I've already done that. If your printer isn't that far off (printing too large or small) it will hold a card.

I wouldn't print this in PLA. Getting the card in requires quite a bit of flexing of the retaining tab, so more flexible plastic like ABS or PETG would be better. I use ABS and it's worked perfectly. Further, an ID badge is the sort of thing you might leave in your car by accident or design, and PLA deforms very quickly in summer car temperatures. It is entirely possible that the PLA will flex enough, as the back/tab is very thin and that makes it more flexible - I just wouldn't bother due to the many shortcomings of PLA for this purpose. Similarly I wouldn't do this in a truly flexible plastic like TPU or Ninjaflex or what have you. It's not needed, and could work against the purpose of the thing.

The little flap that holds the card usually needs a little help opening up the first time. I use a very small blade screwdriver to wiggle it loose.

If your printer isn't fantastic at bridging you will probably have some dangles. There is some play in the slot for the card, so you might try leaving them and test fit your card. If you clean them out, be gentle.

Use 3D Builder, Smoosh Together

I've tried modifying parts with Blender and Meshmixer before, but nothing has been as easy as the 3D Builder program. It's like using TinkerCAD but with STL files. I've been able to get Blender or Meshmixer to do what I wanted, while 3D Builder has been just as easy as TinkerCAD. I hate Windows 10, but I'm loving the 3D Builder.

I scaled down the badge holder to make it "correct" as suggested by the original author. Then I scaled the logo keeping x and y (and z) locked to make it fit on the back of the holder, then when I got it all set and aligned how I wanted it, I unlocked the scaling and made the z match the height of the back of the holder. Finally I merged the parts and saved the STL.

description.text:
Demonstrating things in a Three-Dimensional space is some of the most difficult to do, especially with precision and within a mathematical framework. No matter how many times I looked at an isometric approximation of a 3D Cartesian space, I couldn't perfectly visualize it. For this reason, I created this for my 3D Printing for Teachers class in my graduate work for education. Just recently polishing it, this should be the final version of my standing XYZ Cartesian model, pending feedback from others. There are a few ways to use this device:

1) Place the xy-plane square hole over the z-axis base peg, then slot the z-axis top peg into the combined peg hole. From here, the evenly spaced measurements can be used to give a more precise visual 3D space.
2) Before slotting the z-axis top peg into the combined square hole, tie a thin piece of string around the peg, and then tie the other end to a bead or similar "dot"-like object, to simulate a point in the Cartesian Space. This can also be done with very thin wire to simulate a line or curve starting at the origin.
3) This can also be used just for its xy-plane, or as a visual aid to remember students to think about and visualize the 3D space.

I'd love to hear other uses for the tool, and any feedback.

title: Customizable Optical Rail Mount for OpenBeam

description.text:
This is a modification of http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:30491
I added a bolt to hold the rod in place, fixed the nut orientation, and made it customizable.

The included STL is for 15mm openbeam, 8mm smooth rod, and M3 nuts and bolts.

This is part of a system of prints that turns an Open Beam into an optical rail. An optical rail is a long, straight, sturdy rail onto which optical components such as light sources and lenses can be bolted down and easily shifted along the length of the rail.

Commercial optical rail sells for $250+/m. Open beam only costs $12/m for the fancy black anodized stuff. You get the idea.

This component is inspired by the Open-source optics project, whose goal is to radically reduce the cost of scientific optical hardware, by the Michigan Tech's Open Sustainability Technology Research Group.

UPDATE: now slightly smaller, using measured sizes (and some leeway) for the nuts to reduce slot size. And tighter on the post/rod.

Instructions

OpenSCAD code included for modifications. Just print on your favorite 3D printer and clean up. For stability/strength, this part may need 25% or more infill. I have not needed supports when printing with PLA or ABS.

You'll need 2- M3 Nuts and 2- M3x20/25mm bolts.

The mount slides onto the OpenBeam as seen in the pictures. You secure it in place with a combination of M3 bolts and nuts. Then mount optical components on the 8mm diameter rod.

You can get OpenBeam at http://www.openbeamusa.com/

comments.text: Hey newbpilot. its actually really easy to make the insulation. first assemble the two outer halves of the mold as in picture #1. then fill it about 50% full with high temp silicone. take the inner core from Photo #3 and jam it inside as in picture #2. the fins on the top should help center the inner mold in the outer mold casing. then just make sure that there is enough silicone on top of the inner mold. you may have to either smooth it over the top or add some more silicone. wrap the whole thing in tape to prevent the inner mold from moving and let it dry. then undo the screws or bolts holding the outer mold casing together and carefully remove them. then just carefully work the inner mold out to the insulation. trim up the holes ( they will have a thin skin of silicone over them. and then remove the heater and thermistor from the hotend and work the insulation over the hotend, reinstall the thermistor and the heater and you are done. description.text:
When making Free Body Diagrams for my engineering classes, I found I had to make lots of circles. Having the artistic ability of a walrus, I was often making my wheels into potatoes, asteroids, and amoebas. While compases are nice for larger diagrams, they aren't really good for smaller circles (and it puts a small hole in your nice clean paper).

The guide features 2 sides, one with metric diameters ( in 5mm, 10mm, 15mm and 20mm)

description.text:
As stated this is a work in progress. There are a lot of files because I decided to include the individual chain links so people can arrange them on their own if they want, I've been making these in Tinkercad and using Slic3r to make STL's that I slice in Cura. I've tried to label the files clearly, hopefully everything correctly, and I'll point out a few of the files to look for.

The picture shows the Heart Ver 2 file after it's been broken apart, it's the larger longer piece. It was printed with links at about 7mm high). The heart file came out in pieces when I got the links moving, it's an interesting pixelated looking heart shape when whole. It was far more stuck together than the Ver 1 file provided, the links have less clearance, I think I'll make another version with cutouts and larger eyes. It may not have broken apart if I hadn't been in the middle of machine calibration and some hardware troubleshooting while it was printing.

The smaller piece in the picture is the "Four Walls Linked Ver 1 Works" file. As stated, it works. Links were much easier to get moving than Ver 2. The version pictured has approx 6mm high links.

The Frill Pill files are just now being tested and I expect them to be very nice, except that I'm having trouble figuring out how to make turns with them, so currently can only make a straight line. Hopefully I'll have a picture of them soon. "4x40mmStableFrillPillVerLinkChain" has a short chain of Frill Pill V2 links and is the test file I'm printing (with a brim).

With some work maybe these could be passable fashion accessories, but for me they're just a novelty and design challenge at the moment.

Update: I successfully printed Frill Pill and added a photo. It was a low resolution print (.2MM resolution), which I think helped prevent it from tipping over but of course means it doesn't look as nice as it could.

Update: Added a horizontal Frill Pill file. Likely needs support more than the 45 degree angle ones. I haven't used the 60 degree links yet.

Update: Added some complete chains for frill pill. "cross" makes a cat or small dog sized necklace. BigVer2Good is untested but may hopefully fit a person, who knows.

Link to video

#DSLR_UAV_Gimbal

A video posted by Seth Bullis (@rangler6475) on Nov 25, 2016 at 10:12pm PST

Update 02/22/17
A balancing plate for dslr cameras is here I will allow for the gimbal to be balanced with different lenses. I am planning on machining mine, but have yet to do so. I believe that the 2 1/4 inch bolts to hold the plate in place should be enough. I may change the arm to use smaller bolts due to the lack of strain and excess weight from the larger bolts.

FYI this gimbal does not perform very well with video applications due to plastic flexing and creating a bouncing picture effect. Photography was it's main purpose in producing orthomosaics.

Also the cover for the back fits perfectly, but since my storm 32 had a BEC failure for power from the main board. I can't use the cover due to the USB having to be plugged into the side of the board during use. The storm 32 should be able to be powered strait from the 6s power, but mine requires an additional 5v input. If this happens to you, just run a voltage converter from the main battery to the board. Make sure that it is truly 5 volts or else you may run into problems

This here is my 3d printed gimbal in all it's glory. It has been an unbelievable pain in the ass to troubleshoot, but all in all it works now. This gimbal can support about an 800-1000g camera depending on the motors used and the voltage supplied to those motors. The gimbal is built around the GBM5208 motors and the Storm 32 which allows for 1.5amps for each motor output. If you are using a heavy camera I'd recommend a 6s battery. All of the arms for the gimbal are attached and can be adjusted to balance by 3mm bolts. I used whatever length I had around and added nuts to the bolts to adjust their length when threaded into the motors. Assembly is pretty simple and there are plenty of zip tie areas to make cable management a breeze.

This gimbal is also able to work with any of the tarot copters that are 690mm and smaller with the plate I provided. The plate allows you to attach tarot vibration mounts and mount the whole gimbal onto the rails of the drone.

Comment if you have questions. I can also try to design a bracket for your uav if you need one.

-at least half a spool of abs

This was a personal project that i decided to do, to see if i could make an enclosure to keep the air temperature constant as i am looking to move onto more advanced printing materials that require a more stable environment. The nuts, bolts and washers are ISO M6 & M4 , the rod is ISO M6...it was designed to work with 3mm extruded Acrylic sheeting (However you can easily just use longer bolts if you wish to use thicker sheets) ...The air vents size and shape is obviously up to you and if you wish to use a fan or not, is your choice.

Secondly i decided to do modifications to the generic store-bought cable chain so that it could fit along the X-axis motor mount and linear rail system in a neat,simple and refined manner, without having to reprint it or any other drastic changes, simply remove the end two bracket pieces and clip the rest of the chain onto my 3D printed brackets - and as you can see, it works like a charm for confined spaces.

comments.text: How did you assemble and drill it? Im looking to create this and already have the acrylic sheets.

What i did was very DIY ...i simply stacked the sheets together and on the top surface i placed the corner pieces at each corner - made sure they were 90 Deg angles and then marked the center hole with a center punch piece and a hammer. Then , whilst still stacked i used my dremel drill-press and just bore out the holes .... for the center supports i did the same , found the middle of the sheets, aligned them and repeated the process - but with the different drill bits depending on the required pieces - since it is a cube, all the measurements should be equal anyways, i tried to make it as hassle-free as possible and use as few a tools as possible.

Filled to the brim, this cup should accommodate ~224 ml, which is approx. 1 Cup. Interestingly a scoop of compressible ingredients such as flour can be up to 1.5× the weight of the same volume sifted. Version 1 was made with Blender while version 2 was made with OpenSCAD and has the following advantages:
  • Parametric - 1 Cup, ¼ Cup or any other measure such as ¾ Cup can be generated by changing the parameters if you have OpenSCAD
  • Braced - The joint between the handle and the scoop should be stronger
  • Higher definition - The circles and ellipses should look less polygonal
    • The 1 Cup STL is from Blender while the ¼ Cup measure is exported from OpenSCAD. The walls of the cup are 3 mm wide and the handle 5 mm deep.

To generate a new measuring cup using OpenSCAD, edit the following variables and re-generate the STL:
  • brim_radius - the radius of the circle that defines the top or brim of the scoop
  • base_radius - the radius of the circle that defines the bottom of the scoop
  • scoop_depth - The distance in mm between the brim and the bottom of the scoop
  • divisor - Use 1 for a whole Cup, 4 for a ¼ Cup, and so on
    • Look for the line of output regarding the volume. If the dimensions do not result in the intended volume then a warning will be printed. Please let me know if you how to get OpenSCAD to abort in this situation.

description.text:
This was the solution I designed to prevent bed shaking during acceleration movements and also get a fixed auto level solution (no need for software auto level) while still keep the spring suspension protection that was originally installed.
This is done by setting a fixed height for the table set by the printed parts. The original spring protection suspension is kept under the heated bed to provide the under support for the fixed height and the hotend collision protection.

Can be used in either 4 point or 3 point assembly option.

Assembly

1-Slide the printed auto-level mounts in the printer steel base bed.
2-Insert the spring (inside) in the printed auto-level mounts between the heated bed (bottom) and the of steel base bed (top).
3-Insert the M3 screw from the top hole, going through the spring and exiting the bottom.
4-Insert the M3 nut in the bottom. When tightening the nut should self lock in the socket.
5-Start printing. :-P

description.text:
It all started with change of the platter on my turntable (Goldring GR1.2, which is a clone of Rega P2). It turned out, that the new platter is sitting higher than the old one, and thus I need to raise the arm.
Unfortunatelly, these turntables have not adjustable VTA.

After not being able to find any commercially available and satisfying solution (price!), I've made the adjuster myself. It works perfectly for me.

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.1

Infill:

Dense

Notes:

CURA used to slice and output the gcode.
I've used CPE ESD filament as this was the only black one I've had access to.
This might have another benefit - as this one is a bit more flexble than the PLA, which should work better on a turntable.

The prototype has been printed using gray PLA (also on picture here)

That was fairly simple:

26mm circle for a center hole
50mm circle for an outer edge
This was then extruded to 2mm high

3 supports were made with:
4mm center hole and 8mm outer circle extruded to 4mm high
and then copied around the center with 120 degree distance.
The last thing was to check/fix the geometry to ensure it's printable.

Show off how useful your 3D printer is (and your craft skills) by making some Traditional Christmas Crackers with snapper, joke, toy, & hat!  
Note: The STL file is useless and not required, Thingiverse must have a non-picture file before you can publish anything.

Print out your favorite little trinkets from Thingiverse, making sure you scale them small enough to fit inside a toilet roll. I used the following:
Starfleet command ring http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:12478
Thimble http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:40143

... of course the options are limitless! Cut the streamer end off a party popper (makes it louder and take up less room) and throw it away, keeping the snapper end with string. Poke some holes in the toilet roll and feed the string through like pictured - the idea here is to make a harness for the popper at one end so that pulling each end of the string will set off the explosive (one end is the party popper pull cord, the other is the harness tied to the paper tube). Wrap the party hat (make one out of crepe paper) and a printed joke (I found some at http://www.goodbadjokes.com) around your printed toy and fasten with a rubber band. Insert into the other end of the tube and wrap in wrapping paper (tape the string onto the back of the paper first to ensure the snapper 'snaps' when the cracker ends are pulled). Carefully twist the ends and secure with ribbon. Done! Disclaimer: Party poppers have a small gunpowder 'cap' in them which is potentially dangerous or could catch the paper on fire, etc, use at your own risk. I have tried half a dozen of these so far and haven't had any problems, however I take no responsibility to any damage to property, pets, children, etc.

title: Adjustable Z-Axis Endstop Holder for Prusa i3

description.text:
A simple, easily added Z-axis mechanical endstop holder for the Prusa i3.   
I've included the OpenSCAD files in the event anyone needs to make some changes. I'm still learning, and I hope to have a more easily customizable version up in the future.

The switch holder mounts to the top of the left Z motor, while the adjuster screw holder mounts on the bottom motor mount screw on the left X end. You'll likely need longer motor mount screws for those places with these installed - I know I did.  
Versions of the Adjuster Screw Mount are available for either an M3 or #6 adjuster screw. The captive nut may need a bit of glue to be held in place.

Better photographs coming soon! For now check the Alibre model pictures Having a superb Ultipanel to use with my Ultimaker
I decided holding it by hand was just not doing it justice. So I needed to produce a design that would: Hook on the front or side of the Ultimaker, holding the screen at a good angle without impeding a print. Stand on the table holding the screen at a good angle. Print in two main parts, not requiring glue for assembly. Be Vitamin free. Be robust enough to withstand the odd mishap. Be easy to print Using just the standard quality Ultimaker Netfabb profile (or higher quality if you like). It should also print perfectly well with OS software. The pictures were of my last prototype printing in red PLA. Later I will go with a blue PLA to match the printer.

No great secrets here, just load and print! Note that there are two knob versions, just print the one you like best. I have orientated the STL files in Netfabb so that they should print as such: LCD holder, needs to print face down. Back Plate, prints standing on one end (make sure you get good adhesion on the first layer) Knobs, probably best printed face down Once printed
Clean off any excess plastic. Take particular care to ensure that the seating area on the body of the holder for the back plate is clean, double check the corners! Then carefully check the back plate ensuring that the edges, corners and the tongue (the thinner long edge) are also clear of excess plastic. Assembly easy to do, hard to explain! Step one: Take note of where the encoder spindle (shaft for the knob) and SD card slot are and how they relate to the holder. Also note where the retaining clips are for the Ultipanel. They are on the inside of the two ends of the holder and to my mind look rather like mini ski ramps. Make sure they are clear of excess plastic. Step two Start to insert the Ultipanel(face down of course ;)) starting with the edge of the board closest to the hook part of the holder.Slide to the back of the holder and then level the Ultipanel board out so it is sitting on top of the retaining clips / ski ramps, on the two inside edges of the holder. Make sure that you spindle is aligned with the hole. Step three Starting at the SD slot end, push the circuit board down so that it clips in place. Be careful to push on the circuit board as close to the clip points as possible to reduce flexing moment on the board. Step four Repeat the process on the spindle end of the board, once again pushing as close to the clip as possible. Step fivePlace your chosen knob onto the spindle, use a very small piece of masking tape on the flat of the spindle if the fit is a little loose. If its too tight, don't push overly hard in an attempt to make it fit, you don't want to damage you Ultipanel ;) Step six Feed the plugs through the cut out on the back panel. Check to make sure that the leads will not become twisted before plugging them into the board. Step seven Tuck the thinner long edge of the back plate (the tongue) into the bottom of the holder. Then rotate the back plate down until the right angled flap comes into contact with the hook part of the holder. Step eight Gently squeeze the back panel so that the angled flap tucks under the holder's hook. Then push the flap up into the recess. The back cover should now be flush with the holder. Step nine Time to enjoy your work! Hook it on the front or side of the Ultimaker or just place it on the work surface. Now get back to printing......... ... .
